Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

There remain limited commercial options to return to the UK from Denmark.
If you live in the UK and are currently visiting Denmark, you’re strongly advised to return now by commercial means. Don’t run the risk of getting stranded.
The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) advise that British nationals that wish to leave Denmark contact their travel operator to make arrangements to do so as soon as possible.
Flights from Denmark
Copenhagen and Billund airports remain open. However, there are currently no direct flights from Denmark to the UK after 8 April until further notice. You should refer to carriers’ websites for the latest information on flight availability, including indirect routes, but note that schedules may change.
Flights from Greenland and the Faroe Islands
There are no commercial flights to and from Greenland until at least 30 April. The commercial air service to the Faroe Islands has been severely reduced, with only one daily service to and from Copenhagen on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
Further information
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy Copenhagen on Twitter and Facebook
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
